1
00:01:03,879 --> 00:01:06,814
All of life is a coming home.

2
00:01:06,882 --> 00:01:11,148
Salesmen, secretaries, coal miners,
beekeepers, sword swallowers--

3
00:01:11,219 --> 00:01:13,153
all of us.

4
00:01:13,221 --> 00:01:16,486
All the restless hearts
of the world...

5
00:01:16,558 --> 00:01:19,493
all trying
to find a way home.

6
00:01:21,697 --> 00:01:25,098
It's hard to describe
what I felt like then.

7
00:01:25,167 --> 00:01:28,603
Picture yourself walking
for days in a driving snow.

8
00:01:28,670 --> 00:01:31,605
You don't even know
you're walking in circles--

9
00:01:31,673 --> 00:01:34,608
the heaviness of your legs
in the drifts;

10
00:01:34,676 --> 00:01:37,042
your shouts
disappearing into the wind.

11
00:01:37,112 --> 00:01:39,342
How small you can feel.

12
00:01:39,414 --> 00:01:42,212
How far away home can be.

13
00:01:59,368 --> 00:02:01,393
Home.

14
00:02:01,470 --> 00:02:04,906
The dictionary defines it
as both a place of origin...

15
00:02:04,973 --> 00:02:07,032
and a goal or destination.

16
00:02:08,477 --> 00:02:10,411
And the storm?

17
00:02:10,479 --> 00:02:13,243
The storm was all in my mind.

18
00:02:13,315 --> 00:02:15,579
Or, as the poet Dante put it...

19
00:02:15,651 --> 00:02:19,348
"In the middle of the journey of my life
I found myself in a dark wood...

20
00:02:19,421 --> 00:02:21,855
for I had lost
the right path."

21
00:02:22,991 --> 00:02:25,789
Eventually I would find
the right path...

22
00:02:25,861 --> 00:02:28,694
but in the most unlikely place.

23
00:03:00,529 --> 00:03:02,463
How many fingers
do you see?

24
00:03:02,531 --> 00:03:04,965
You crazy--
Stop sneakin' up on me like that.

25
00:03:05,033 --> 00:03:06,762
How many?

26
00:03:06,835 --> 00:03:09,463
- Four.
- Four?

27
00:03:09,538 --> 00:03:11,972
Four?

28
00:03:12,040 --> 00:03:13,974
Another idiot.

29
00:03:15,143 --> 00:03:17,202
You gon' love it here.

30
00:03:18,280 --> 00:03:20,714
Got a new one, Jane.
Hunter Adams.

31
00:03:20,782 --> 00:03:23,717
Self-committed. Suicidal.
Slate him with Dr. Prack.

32
00:03:23,785 --> 00:03:25,719
All right.

33
00:03:33,161 --> 00:03:36,289
Hey, Rudy!
What's the word, my man?

34
00:03:36,364 --> 00:03:39,925
He ain't left that bed in three weeks.
He won't give you any trouble.

35
00:03:40,001 --> 00:03:43,232
He needs another bedpan. They're in
the closet. Wake-up is 7:00 a.m.

36
00:03:43,305 --> 00:03:45,239
Excuse me.

37
00:03:45,307 --> 00:03:48,299
Is there any way
I could have my own room?

38
00:03:49,711 --> 00:03:51,838
Oh, absolutely.

39
00:03:51,913 --> 00:03:54,643
Just call the concierge and ask
for a suite overlooking the fountain.

40
00:03:54,716 --> 00:03:57,150
No, l-l prefer
the cabana room.

41
00:03:57,219 --> 00:03:59,278
Get some sleep.

42
00:04:10,332 --> 00:04:12,266
Hi.

43
00:04:14,136 --> 00:04:16,195
Hi.

44
00:04:19,908 --> 00:04:21,842
You're, um...

45
00:04:23,044 --> 00:04:26,707
you're a lot... fuzzier
than my last roommate.

46
00:04:26,782 --> 00:04:28,374
Oh. Yeah.

47
00:04:28,450 --> 00:04:30,384
Keeps me warm.

48
00:04:31,453 --> 00:04:34,013
Aaaah!

49
00:04:36,191 --> 00:04:38,819
- What's wrong?
- Get 'em away!

50
00:04:38,894 --> 00:04:41,727
- Get what away?
- Get 'em-- Get 'em away!

51
00:04:41,797 --> 00:04:44,288
- Okay, I'm gonna have to--
- You traitor!

52
00:04:44,366 --> 00:04:48,496
You brought 'em with you
when you opened the door!

53
00:04:48,570 --> 00:04:51,368
Who?

54
00:04:53,375 --> 00:04:56,310
We need help in here!

55
00:04:56,378 --> 00:04:58,312
Somebody!

56
00:05:00,882 --> 00:05:02,816
- All right.
- No! No! No!

57
00:05:02,884 --> 00:05:06,911
They'll get me! Don't take me down!
They'll get me! No!

58
00:05:06,988 --> 00:05:09,923
Don't let the squirrels get me!
Please!

59
00:05:09,991 --> 00:05:11,720
Don't let the squirrels get me!

60
00:05:14,796 --> 00:05:17,731
That was a squirrel bite!

61
00:05:17,799 --> 00:05:19,892
Squirrels.

62
00:05:22,237 --> 00:05:25,172
My father died when I was nine.

63
00:05:25,240 --> 00:05:29,336
He was in the army.
He wasn't home very much.

64
00:05:30,478 --> 00:05:33,413
Two weeks before he died...

65
00:05:33,481 --> 00:05:36,416
he told me that
in the Korean War...

66
00:05:36,484 --> 00:05:38,918
it felt like
he'd lost his soul.

67
00:05:38,987 --> 00:05:42,582
All this time
I thought it was me.

68
00:05:42,657 --> 00:05:46,593
I moved seven times
in the last year.

69
00:05:46,661 --> 00:05:49,255
I've, uh, had several jobs.

70
00:05:51,166 --> 00:05:53,100
Nothing seemed to fit.

71
00:05:53,168 --> 00:05:55,102
I don't seem to fit.

72
00:05:57,672 --> 00:06:01,039
And when your father died,
how did that make you feel?

73
00:06:01,109 --> 00:06:03,873
I don't know.
I was nine.

74
00:06:05,447 --> 00:06:08,780
It was like there was
this distinction, suddenly...

75
00:06:08,850 --> 00:06:11,785
between you
and the rest of the world.

76
00:06:11,853 --> 00:06:13,787
I looked around me.

77
00:06:13,855 --> 00:06:17,416
Life went on
just like it did before.

78
00:06:17,492 --> 00:06:20,757
But it wasn't
like it was before.

79
00:06:20,829 --> 00:06:23,764
My uncle helped.
He would visit.

80
00:06:23,832 --> 00:06:25,766
He at least listened.

81
00:06:27,469 --> 00:06:29,460
And I thought...

82
00:06:29,537 --> 00:06:34,497
if I could light my own farts I could
fly to the moon, or at least Uranus.

83
00:06:34,576 --> 00:06:38,103
But if I couldn't do that at least
I could use my penis as a pogo stick...

84
00:06:38,179 --> 00:06:41,114
and that might be a way
of getting around.

85
00:06:41,182 --> 00:06:43,480
I'm sorry?

86
00:06:43,551 --> 00:06:45,485
Yes, that's good.
Mm-hmm.

87
00:06:47,289 --> 00:06:50,781
Well, I think you're making
fine progress, Hunter.
We'll talk later in group.

88
00:06:51,860 --> 00:06:53,794
Thank you.

89
00:07:02,570 --> 00:07:07,007
Four. Four? Four!

90
00:07:07,075 --> 00:07:10,374
Ohh! Four! Ohh!

91
00:07:10,445 --> 00:07:14,506
You are all insane!
lnsane! Four!

92
00:07:14,582 --> 00:07:16,675
Arthur Mendelson.

93
00:07:18,086 --> 00:07:20,020
The Arthur Mendelson?

94
00:07:20,088 --> 00:07:22,215
Brand Beaton lndustries.

95
00:07:22,290 --> 00:07:25,225
Guy was one of the most
innovative minds of our time.

96
00:07:25,293 --> 00:07:28,228
Look at him now.
He can't even count the windows.

97
00:07:30,365 --> 00:07:33,300
God. What happened to him?
Why is he here?

98
00:07:33,368 --> 00:07:37,065
Self-committed. Genius syndrome.
Howard Hughes-type shit.

99
00:07:37,138 --> 00:07:40,665
Constantly digging into the
creative potential of the human mind.

100
00:07:43,244 --> 00:07:45,508
I guess he dug too deep.

101
00:07:45,580 --> 00:07:47,548
This is real wood.

102
00:07:47,615 --> 00:07:50,175
Rowff!

103
00:07:53,421 --> 00:07:57,016
W-Why are we meeting in here?
It's cramped.

104
00:07:57,092 --> 00:08:00,528
Well, Everton, we're meeting in here
so that Rudy can participate.

105
00:08:00,595 --> 00:08:03,564
- It's cramped.
- Does anyone else
have a thought on that?

106
00:08:03,631 --> 00:08:06,998
- Cramped!
- I think he has a question.

107
00:08:09,070 --> 00:08:12,506
Do you find that funny, Hunter,
making fun of a man's infirmity?

108
00:08:12,574 --> 00:08:15,168
Maybe he does have a question.
He's alive.

109
00:08:15,243 --> 00:08:18,178
- He's catatonic.
- Well, he still has a brain.

110
00:08:18,246 --> 00:08:21,010
- Maybe he wants to participate too.
- Yeah.

111
00:08:21,082 --> 00:08:23,016
Maybe he has a question.

112
00:08:23,084 --> 00:08:25,018
Yeah, maybe.

113
00:08:25,086 --> 00:08:27,281
Maybe he knows why we're cramped!

114
00:08:30,358 --> 00:08:33,953
Maybe Beany knows a lot more
than we give him credit for.

115
00:08:34,029 --> 00:08:36,930
Excuse me. Beany?
Which way is heaven?

116
00:08:36,998 --> 00:08:38,932
That's correct!

117
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,467
That'll be enough, Hunter.

118
00:08:40,535 --> 00:08:43,595
Beany, how much taller
is Wilt Chamberlain than you?

119
00:08:43,671 --> 00:08:45,798
- Right.

120
00:08:45,874 --> 00:08:49,037
Hey, Beany! Beany!
Where's the ceiling?

121
00:08:49,110 --> 00:08:51,408
That's enough. Stop it.

122
00:08:51,479 --> 00:08:54,039
Where do the birds fly, Beany?

123
00:08:54,115 --> 00:08:56,049
How do you say hello to Hitler?

124
00:08:56,117 --> 00:08:59,917
Beany, how does Hitler say hello?

125
00:09:01,356 --> 00:09:05,725
How do you check
an elephant for a hernia?

126
00:09:05,794 --> 00:09:09,127
Who would win a staring contest?
Beany!

127
00:09:09,197 --> 00:09:11,165
Who-- Who farted?

128
00:09:11,232 --> 00:09:13,325
Beany!

129
00:09:13,401 --> 00:09:16,268
- Who likes to masturbate?
- Yea!

130
00:09:16,337 --> 00:09:18,305
I do! I do!

131
00:09:18,373 --> 00:09:22,309
Hey, Beany, how does an
one-armed referee say "field goal"?

132
00:09:22,377 --> 00:09:24,004
Ha ha! Hey, Beany!

133
00:09:24,079 --> 00:09:27,446
Ciao, Beany!
Arigato, Beany!

134
00:09:27,515 --> 00:09:29,449
Bye, Beany.

135
00:09:31,986 --> 00:09:34,045
It was a really good session,
I thought.

136
00:09:50,126 --> 00:09:52,060
May I come in?

137
00:09:53,363 --> 00:09:55,797
If you bend your medial
collateral ligaments...

138
00:09:55,865 --> 00:09:58,299
and place one talus
in front of another...

139
00:09:58,368 --> 00:10:00,802
I don't see where
you'd have a problem.

140
00:10:00,870 --> 00:10:03,805
Of course, if there were a news story
covering this event...

141
00:10:03,873 --> 00:10:06,899
the headline might read:
"Small Brain Enters Room."

142
00:10:09,412 --> 00:10:12,245
The fingers.
What's the answer?

143
00:10:12,315 --> 00:10:15,250
Oh, you're another one of
those bright young fellows...

144
00:10:15,318 --> 00:10:18,253
who always know the right answer,
is that it?

145
00:10:18,321 --> 00:10:20,482
Welcome to real life.

146
00:10:55,992 --> 00:10:57,926
How many do you see?

147
00:11:00,463 --> 00:11:03,398
- There are four fingers, Arthur.
- No, no, no. Look at me.

148
00:11:03,466 --> 00:11:05,229
What?

149
00:11:05,301 --> 00:11:07,235
Y-You're focusing
on the problem.

150
00:11:07,303 --> 00:11:10,397
If you focus on the problem,
you can't see the solution.

151
00:11:10,473 --> 00:11:13,670
Never focus on the problem.
Look at me!

152
00:11:14,977 --> 00:11:17,571
How many do you see?

153
00:11:19,248 --> 00:11:22,843
No, look beyond the fingers.

154
00:11:22,919 --> 00:11:24,853
How many do you see?

155
00:11:30,426 --> 00:11:32,360
Eight.

156
00:11:32,428 --> 00:11:35,420
Eight. Eight.
Yes! Yes!

157
00:11:35,498 --> 00:11:38,467
Eight's a good answer.
Yes.

158
00:11:38,534 --> 00:11:40,934
See what no one else sees.

159
00:11:41,003 --> 00:11:43,733
See what everyone else
chooses not to see...

160
00:11:43,806 --> 00:11:46,866
out of fear
and conformity and laziness.

161
00:11:46,943 --> 00:11:50,242
See the whole world anew
each day.

162
00:11:51,747 --> 00:11:54,682
Ah, the truth is,
you're well on the way.

163
00:11:54,750 --> 00:11:57,685
If you didn't
see something here...

164
00:11:57,753 --> 00:12:01,018
besides a crazy,
bitter old man...

165
00:12:01,090 --> 00:12:04,025
you wouldn't have come
in the first place.

166
00:12:07,530 --> 00:12:10,465
What do you see
when you look at me, Arthur?

167
00:12:14,704 --> 00:12:16,638
You fixed my cup.

168
00:12:18,207 --> 00:12:20,141
I'll see you around...

169
00:12:21,444 --> 00:12:23,378
Patch.

170
00:12:31,153 --> 00:12:33,587
Rudy, stop.

171
00:12:33,656 --> 00:12:36,090
You're throwing off
my rhythm.

172
00:12:36,158 --> 00:12:38,092
You'll go blind.

173
00:12:39,262 --> 00:12:41,924
- Please.
- I have to go to the bathroom.

174
00:12:41,998 --> 00:12:45,934
Then go. It's right over there,
15 feet away.

175
00:12:46,002 --> 00:12:49,961
- I would, but--
- But what? The squirrels?

176
00:12:50,039 --> 00:12:52,473
- How many?
- There's only one just now.

177
00:12:53,809 --> 00:12:56,903
You can't go to the bathroom
because of one squirrel?

178
00:12:56,979 --> 00:12:59,812
If I get off the bed,
he'll get the others.

179
00:13:01,050 --> 00:13:02,984
That's not the point.

180
00:13:03,052 --> 00:13:04,986
They're squirrels.

181
00:13:05,054 --> 00:13:07,079
Squirrels, Rudy.

182
00:13:07,156 --> 00:13:11,092
- They're one of the most amiable
creatures on the planet.
- Oh, no, they're not.

183
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:14,095
On the list of hostile predators,
they're right above the bottom...

184
00:13:14,163 --> 00:13:16,757
just above baby chicks
and slugs.

185
00:13:16,832 --> 00:13:19,323
What could they possibly want?
Your nuts?

186
00:13:20,403 --> 00:13:22,837
- Do you think?
- Oh, Rudy.

187
00:13:22,905 --> 00:13:25,999
- Come on, I'll take you.
- Don't move.

188
00:13:26,075 --> 00:13:29,340
- Don't move.
- Another one?

189
00:13:30,813 --> 00:13:34,146
It's on the end of your bed,
on the rail.

190
00:13:38,220 --> 00:13:41,189
Be careful.
It's gonna jump.

191
00:13:53,235 --> 00:13:55,795
- There's one, at the end of the bed!
- Bang!

192
00:13:55,871 --> 00:13:58,806
There's one runnin'
across the sprinkler!

193
00:13:58,874 --> 00:14:01,206
- Boom!
- In back of the door!
Back of the door!

194
00:14:01,277 --> 00:14:04,212
Coming out of the bathroom!

195
00:14:04,280 --> 00:14:06,714
Bathroom! Bathroom!
Bathroom! Bathroom!

196
00:14:06,782 --> 00:14:09,182
Yea!

197
00:14:09,251 --> 00:14:12,982
Eat lead, fur bag!
Blam! Ha-ha!

198
00:14:13,055 --> 00:14:16,491
- You're cured-- Aaah!
- You've got one on your shoulder!

199
00:14:16,559 --> 00:14:19,187
Get it off me! Get it off me!

200
00:14:19,261 --> 00:14:22,594
Get it off me! Aaaah!

201
00:14:24,233 --> 00:14:27,168
We need more cover!
They're comin' in the back door!

202
00:14:27,236 --> 00:14:30,763
- Get under cover, Rudy!
- Build a fort! Build a fort!
We can build a fort!

203
00:14:30,840 --> 00:14:35,106
- We need a fort!
- Aaah! Down! Get down!

204
00:14:38,881 --> 00:14:40,815
They're gone.

205
00:14:40,883 --> 00:14:43,818
I think it's safe to go
to the bathroom, Rudy. Come on.

206
00:14:43,886 --> 00:14:46,480
- No, it's too risky.
- No.

207
00:14:46,555 --> 00:14:48,489
Not when you have...

208
00:14:49,558 --> 00:14:51,492
this.

209
00:14:51,560 --> 00:14:54,495
- A bazooka.
- Yeah.

210
00:14:54,563 --> 00:14:56,497
Load.

211
00:15:01,070 --> 00:15:04,301
- Let's do it!
- Aaaah!

212
00:15:21,757 --> 00:15:23,691
Yes.

213
00:15:31,801 --> 00:15:33,735
I'd like to leave.

214
00:15:35,304 --> 00:15:38,467
Hunter, we'll have to discuss this
at your scheduled time.

215
00:15:38,541 --> 00:15:40,475
I'm leaving.

216
00:15:41,577 --> 00:15:43,511
Have you thought
about what you'll do?

217
00:15:43,579 --> 00:15:46,013
I want to help people.

218
00:15:46,082 --> 00:15:49,574
Last night with Rudy,
I connected to another human being.

219
00:15:49,652 --> 00:15:53,918
I want more of that.
I want to learn about people,
help them with their troubles.

220
00:15:53,989 --> 00:15:56,321
- That's what I do.
- But you suck at it.

221
00:15:56,392 --> 00:15:59,327
You don't even look at people
when they're talking.

222
00:15:59,395 --> 00:16:01,989
I want to listen,
really listen to people.

223
00:16:02,064 --> 00:16:06,592
I can't allow you to leave. I believe
you still have some issues to work out.

224
00:16:06,669 --> 00:16:10,105
Ah. Well, I don't need your permission
because I admitted myself.

225
00:16:10,172 --> 00:16:12,106
- Hunter.
- Mm-hmm?

226
00:16:12,174 --> 00:16:15,610
I must warn you
my report will read "A.M.A."--

227
00:16:15,678 --> 00:16:18,841
that you were signed out of this
hospital "against medical advice."

228
00:16:18,914 --> 00:16:22,008
And my report will read
"I.D.G.A.R.A."

229
00:16:22,084 --> 00:16:24,518
"I don't give a rat's ass."

230
00:16:25,921 --> 00:16:27,855
And my name is Patch.

231
00:17:03,305 --> 00:17:05,739
Hello.
How you doin'?

232
00:17:05,808 --> 00:17:07,742
How do you do?

233
00:17:10,045 --> 00:17:12,479
Hey, this is a nice room.

234
00:17:12,548 --> 00:17:16,143
- May I help you?
- Yeah, I could really use
a foot massage right now.

235
00:17:17,553 --> 00:17:19,487
Rephrasing:
What are you doing here?

236
00:17:19,555 --> 00:17:21,989
I'm your new roommate.
I-l'm moving in.

237
00:17:24,260 --> 00:17:28,629
I don't mean to be rude,
but aren't you a little old
to be starting medical school?

238
00:17:28,697 --> 00:17:31,723
You know, Babe Ruth was 39
when he joined the Yankees.

239
00:17:31,801 --> 00:17:33,735
- No, he wasn't.
- You're right.

240
00:17:33,803 --> 00:17:37,899
But I could really use
an example like that, and if
you ever find one, let me know.

241
00:17:39,742 --> 00:17:42,040
Hi. Patch Adams.

242
00:17:42,111 --> 00:17:44,545
Mitch Vroman.
Georgetown University.

243
00:17:44,613 --> 00:17:47,639
I was awarded the William F. Thompson
Scientific Achievement Award.

244
00:17:47,716 --> 00:17:49,650
Mmm. Emerson Elementary.

245
00:17:49,718 --> 00:17:53,552
I once drew a picture of a rabbit
that got me two gold stars.

246
00:17:55,724 --> 00:17:59,057
I'm gonna go
back over there now.

247
00:18:03,132 --> 00:18:06,397
First do no harm.

248
00:18:06,468 --> 00:18:10,802
What is implicit in this
simple precept of medicine?

249
00:18:11,941 --> 00:18:14,068
An awesome power.

250
00:18:14,143 --> 00:18:16,577
The power to do harm.

251
00:18:18,047 --> 00:18:20,379
Who gives you this power?

252
00:18:20,449 --> 00:18:22,542
The patient.

253
00:18:22,618 --> 00:18:25,917
A patient will come to you
at his moment of greatest dread..

254
00:18:25,988 --> 00:18:29,822
hand you a knife and say,
"Doctor, cut me open."

255
00:18:29,892 --> 00:18:31,860
Why?

256
00:18:31,927 --> 00:18:34,088
Because he trusts you.

257
00:18:34,163 --> 00:18:37,530
He trusts you
the way a child trusts.

258
00:18:37,600 --> 00:18:42,560
He trusts you
to do no harm.

259
00:18:42,638 --> 00:18:45,266
The sad fact is...

260
00:18:45,341 --> 00:18:47,809
human beings
are not worthy of trust.

261
00:18:48,911 --> 00:18:50,845
It is human nature to lie...

262
00:18:50,913 --> 00:18:54,178
take shortcuts,
to lose your nerve, get tired...

263
00:18:54,250 --> 00:18:56,650
make mistakes.

264
00:18:56,719 --> 00:19:00,314
No rational patient would
put his trust in a human being...

265
00:19:00,389 --> 00:19:02,823
and were not gonna let him!

266
00:19:02,892 --> 00:19:05,019
It is our mission here...

267
00:19:05,094 --> 00:19:09,121
to rigorously and ruthlessly
train the humanity out of you...

268
00:19:09,198 --> 00:19:11,530
and make you
into something better.

269
00:19:12,902 --> 00:19:15,837
We're gonna make doctors
out of you.

270
00:19:32,521 --> 00:19:34,455
Two years of studying.

271
00:19:34,523 --> 00:19:37,458
I thought we'd have more contact
with patients. Didn't you?

272
00:19:37,526 --> 00:19:39,460
Hi. I'm Patch.

273
00:19:39,528 --> 00:19:41,962
You've just experienced
a North American greeting...

274
00:19:42,031 --> 00:19:44,465
whereby one person offers
a verbal label to another...

275
00:19:44,533 --> 00:19:46,967
as an expression
of welcome and friendship.

276
00:19:47,036 --> 00:19:49,163
Lesbian. Ball-buster.
Airhead. Leech.

277
00:19:49,238 --> 00:19:52,173
Whichever one of these disgusts
you the most, take your pick.

278
00:19:52,241 --> 00:19:54,175
- Well--
- Please pass the word.

279
00:19:54,243 --> 00:19:57,679
I am not here to date. I am not
here to flirt. I'm here to study.

280
00:19:59,748 --> 00:20:01,682
Thank you.

281
00:20:01,750 --> 00:20:05,186
I thought only I could repel women
with that kind of raw efficiency.

282
00:20:05,254 --> 00:20:08,018
Well, you just met your match.

283
00:20:08,090 --> 00:20:10,354
- Patch Adams.
- Truman Schiff.

284
00:20:10,426 --> 00:20:12,860
Nice to meet you, Truman.

285
00:20:12,928 --> 00:20:15,021
Will you go out with me?

286
00:20:18,867 --> 00:20:21,495
May I ask you one question?

287
00:20:21,570 --> 00:20:25,062
- Do you buy everything
the dean was saying today?
- What do you mean?

288
00:20:25,140 --> 00:20:27,574
I mean, that whole
drill sergeant thing.

289
00:20:27,643 --> 00:20:30,874
"We're gon' make doctors
out of you medical scum.

290
00:20:30,946 --> 00:20:33,380
- Now drop down and give me 20."
- Mm-hmm.

291
00:20:33,449 --> 00:20:35,007
That whole marine thing.

292
00:20:35,084 --> 00:20:38,019
We're not even gonna see
a patient until the third year.

293
00:20:38,087 --> 00:20:40,021
Up until then,
it's just memorizing facts.

294
00:20:40,089 --> 00:20:42,023
-Why don't they just shove the book up--
-Hamburger?

295
00:20:42,091 --> 00:20:46,118
Right here on the colon. That's where
it's going anyway. Thanks very much.

296
00:20:46,195 --> 00:20:48,891
- So, why do you wanna be a doctor?
- I want to help.

297
00:20:48,964 --> 00:20:53,025
I want to connect with people.
A doctor interacts with people
at their most vulnerable.

298
00:20:53,102 --> 00:20:56,367
He offers treatment,
but he also offers counsel and hope.

299
00:20:56,438 --> 00:20:59,373
That's why I love the idea
of being a doctor.

300
00:20:59,441 --> 00:21:02,706
I've always been fascinated by
the development of the human mind.

301
00:21:02,778 --> 00:21:04,939
Ah. Pumping neurons.

302
00:21:05,014 --> 00:21:07,448
We start out so open
and spontaneous.

303
00:21:07,516 --> 00:21:10,952
We're real individuals. Then somewhere
along the way we're drawn to conform.

304
00:21:11,020 --> 00:21:14,615
- It's as if we're conditioned
by programmed responses.
- Well, that's true.

305
00:21:14,690 --> 00:21:17,625
But sometimes you can alter
the programmed response...

306
00:21:17,693 --> 00:21:21,823
just by changing some of the conditions,
altering the parameters.

307
00:21:21,897 --> 00:21:23,797
Let me show you.

308
00:21:24,967 --> 00:21:26,901
We'll call it
the "hello" experiment.

309
00:21:26,969 --> 00:21:29,403
The goal will be to break through
programmed response...

310
00:21:29,471 --> 00:21:31,405
by changing normal parameters...

311
00:21:31,473 --> 00:21:33,270
and getting a new emotional response
from the person.

312
00:21:33,342 --> 00:21:35,276
Ready to enter data.

313
00:21:37,079 --> 00:21:39,013
Hello.

314
00:21:39,081 --> 00:21:41,345
Hi.

315
00:21:45,287 --> 00:21:47,221
Wait.
I don't get it.

316
00:21:47,289 --> 00:21:49,416
"Hi" is a programmed response.

317
00:21:49,491 --> 00:21:52,051
- I reached her.
- You scared her.

318
00:21:52,127 --> 00:21:55,290
No. Wait.
Wait for it.

319
00:21:56,498 --> 00:21:58,932
Oh, you're nuts.

320
00:21:59,001 --> 00:22:01,526
A smile.

321
00:22:01,603 --> 00:22:04,197
Ten seconds.
Victory.

322
00:22:04,273 --> 00:22:06,537
There's more.
Come, my friend.

323
00:22:08,143 --> 00:22:10,077
- Howdy!
- Hi.

324
00:22:10,145 --> 00:22:12,079
See?
Response time is diminishing.

325
00:22:12,147 --> 00:22:14,581
Yesterday I made
12 random phone calls.

326
00:22:14,650 --> 00:22:18,086
I talked to one man named Dale for
three hours. He told me amazing things.

327
00:22:18,153 --> 00:22:21,088
But what does this all prove,
other than you're out of your mind?

328
00:22:21,156 --> 00:22:24,091
What's the difference between
a doctor and a scientist?

329
00:22:24,159 --> 00:22:26,093
And don't say salary.

330
00:22:26,161 --> 00:22:29,597
People. Hmm? We want to become doctors
because we want to help people.

331
00:22:29,665 --> 00:22:31,599
I want to be
a pediatrician.

332
00:22:31,667 --> 00:22:33,601
Okay, little people.

333
00:22:33,669 --> 00:22:37,105
The point is, we have to treat
the patient as well as the disease.

334
00:22:37,172 --> 00:22:42,269
That's why we have to dive into people,
wade into the sea of humanity, Truman.

335
00:22:42,344 --> 00:22:44,904
Ballroom seven,
right upstairs on your left.

336
00:22:44,980 --> 00:22:48,916
- You guys with
the meat packers convention?
- Yes, sir!

337
00:22:48,984 --> 00:22:50,918
Right up the stairs.
Ballroom seven.

338
00:22:50,986 --> 00:22:53,921
- Hey! Does a chicken have lips?
- You'll find out upstairs!

339
00:22:53,989 --> 00:22:56,514
Like a bulldog
on a pork chop!

340
00:23:08,103 --> 00:23:11,038
You know, in New Zealand
they found a whole new use for sheep.

341
00:23:11,106 --> 00:23:13,040
- What's that?
- Wool!

342
00:23:14,309 --> 00:23:17,244
You're funny!
You kill me! You kill me!

343
00:23:17,312 --> 00:23:19,246
- I love you!
- Oh, daddy!

344
00:23:19,314 --> 00:23:22,249
And you-- I bet you've heard that too!
Come here! Ha ha!

345
00:23:22,317 --> 00:23:24,979
- "Herd" it? That's a goat joke!
- Ohh!

346
00:23:34,496 --> 00:23:36,430
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

347
00:23:39,201 --> 00:23:41,396
On your meat!

348
00:23:41,470 --> 00:23:43,904
Get set! Go!

349
00:23:45,874 --> 00:23:49,071
Ohh! Yeah!

350
00:23:50,145 --> 00:23:52,443
I won!

351
00:23:55,450 --> 00:23:59,113
Pork packers,
rump wrappers, bull shippers,

352
00:23:59,188 --> 00:24:02,055
Iend me your steers!

353
00:24:05,360 --> 00:24:10,457
You know, we packers have been
taking a bad rap for years.

354
00:24:10,532 --> 00:24:12,966
Yeah!

355
00:24:13,035 --> 00:24:17,165
Because we all want to be
the best damn packers there are!

356
00:24:17,239 --> 00:24:20,265
- Yeah!
- Yeah!
- I'm proud of my meat!

357
00:24:20,342 --> 00:24:22,833
- And I know you're proud of your meat!
- Yeah!

358
00:24:22,911 --> 00:24:25,812
- Whip it, zip it and send it out!
- Yeah!

359
00:24:27,883 --> 00:24:29,976
You know,
some people say chicken.

360
00:24:30,052 --> 00:24:31,246
- No!
- No!

361
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:33,618
- Some people say fish.
- No!

362
00:24:33,689 --> 00:24:38,285
I say,
now is the time for cow!

363
00:24:40,362 --> 00:24:43,195
Eat cow! Eat cow! Eat cow! Eat cow!

364
00:24:43,265 --> 00:24:47,497
Eat cow! Eat cow!
Eat cow! Eat cow! Eat cow!

365
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:51,300
Eat cow! Eat cow!
Eat cow! Eat cow! Eat cow!

366
00:24:51,373 --> 00:24:53,341
Hey, bud.

367
00:24:53,408 --> 00:24:55,603
- Hey!
- Oh!

368
00:24:55,677 --> 00:24:58,771
Yes, thanks.
Oh, yeah.

369
00:24:58,847 --> 00:25:02,283
Hey-- Whoa!

370
00:25:02,351 --> 00:25:04,285
What is it?

371
00:25:04,353 --> 00:25:08,541
What's the difference
between a first-year
and a third-year medical student?

372
00:25:13,513 --> 00:25:17,950
Doctor Vukov, please dial line 1242.

373
00:25:18,017 --> 00:25:21,783
Dr. Vukov,
please dial line 1242.

374
00:25:24,023 --> 00:25:26,457
Here we have
a juvenile onset diabetic...

375
00:25:26,526 --> 00:25:29,689
with poor circulation
and diabetic neuropathy.

376
00:25:29,763 --> 00:25:32,698
As you can see,
these are diabetic ulcers...

377
00:25:32,766 --> 00:25:34,961
with lymphedema
and evidence of gangrene.

378
00:25:35,034 --> 00:25:36,968
Questions?

379
00:25:37,036 --> 00:25:39,664
- Any osteomyelitis?
- None apparent.

380
00:25:39,739 --> 00:25:41,297
Although not definitive.

381
00:25:41,374 --> 00:25:43,501
- Treatment?
- To stabilize the blood sugar.

382
00:25:43,576 --> 00:25:46,306
Consider antibiotics,
possibly amputation.

383
00:25:46,379 --> 00:25:48,472
What's her name?

384
00:25:52,719 --> 00:25:55,688
I was just wondering
the patient's name.

385
00:25:57,690 --> 00:25:59,624
Marjorie.

386
00:26:00,994 --> 00:26:02,621
Hi, Marjorie.

387
00:26:02,695 --> 00:26:04,322
Hi.

388
00:26:05,432 --> 00:26:07,957
Yes, um, thank you.

389
00:26:08,034 --> 00:26:09,968
Let's move on.

390
00:26:12,372 --> 00:26:15,307
- What are you doing?
- Continuing the experiment. Come on.

391
00:26:15,375 --> 00:26:18,310
We can start a lemonade stand
together after we get kicked out
of medical school.

392
00:26:18,378 --> 00:26:20,073
Bye, Marjorie.

393
00:26:20,146 --> 00:26:23,081
I cannot stand it in there, Joletta.

394
00:26:23,149 --> 00:26:26,084
He doesn't have
to talk to me like that.

395
00:26:26,152 --> 00:26:29,588
I know, hon, but really,
how good a mood would you be in?

396
00:26:30,723 --> 00:26:34,022
- May I help you?
- Oh, um--

397
00:26:34,093 --> 00:26:37,028
So I'll meet you
at the club.

398
00:26:37,096 --> 00:26:40,691
Oh, great.
Maybe we'll play the back nine, hmm?

399
00:26:42,168 --> 00:26:45,103
Hello. I'm Patch.

400
00:26:45,171 --> 00:26:47,105
I'm studying medicine here.

401
00:26:47,173 --> 00:26:51,234
Well, not here, but--
Y-You know.

402
00:26:51,311 --> 00:26:54,109
Lookit here, Judy.
Another future boss.

403
00:26:54,180 --> 00:26:56,239
Oh, I wouldn't
look at it like that.

404
00:26:56,316 --> 00:26:58,250
You may think
I'm exaggeratin'...

405
00:26:58,318 --> 00:27:01,185
but in another five years
you'll be so full of yourself...

406
00:27:01,254 --> 00:27:04,849
you'll have to hang a cup out your ass
just to catch the excess.

407
00:27:04,924 --> 00:27:07,392
- Joletta!
- Ouch.
- Well, hell, why not?

408
00:27:07,460 --> 00:27:10,395
It's the only time in my life
I'm gonna outrank him.

409
00:27:10,463 --> 00:27:12,931
Might as well enjoy it.

410
00:27:12,999 --> 00:27:16,992
- Who's in that room?
- Don't even think about it.
He'll bite your head off.

411
00:27:17,070 --> 00:27:19,265
Mr. Davis.
Pancreatic cancer.

412
00:27:20,440 --> 00:27:22,374
How long does he have?

413
00:27:22,442 --> 00:27:25,377
Longer than you,
if you go in that room.

414
00:27:25,445 --> 00:27:27,538
So be sure
you steer clear.

415
00:27:27,614 --> 00:27:30,208
Yes, ma'am.
Thank you.

416
00:27:33,019 --> 00:27:35,385
Hey!
What year are you?

417
00:27:40,693 --> 00:27:42,627
- Hi.
- Hey.

418
00:27:51,371 --> 00:27:54,238
Dr. Landaker to Administration.

419
00:27:54,307 --> 00:27:56,741
Dr. Landaker
to Administration, please.

420
00:28:26,072 --> 00:28:28,006
Hi.

421
00:28:28,074 --> 00:28:29,939
Hi.

422
00:28:30,009 --> 00:28:32,705
- What's your name?
- Cameron.

423
00:28:32,779 --> 00:28:36,044
Hi, Cameron.
I'm Patch.

424
00:28:57,203 --> 00:29:00,536
I have a cold. Just a bit of a cold.

425
00:29:00,607 --> 00:29:04,373
Is my nose red?
Oh, it is. It's red.

426
00:29:06,079 --> 00:29:09,071
Ohh! Oh.

427
00:29:09,148 --> 00:29:11,378
What's that?
You don't know?

428
00:29:11,451 --> 00:29:13,385
I don't either.
Let's find out.

429
00:29:14,954 --> 00:29:16,888
Taxi!

430
00:29:16,956 --> 00:29:19,891
Try on you.
Give it to me.

431
00:29:22,729 --> 00:29:25,664
It's working very well.

432
00:29:25,732 --> 00:29:27,859
Let's see what else we have.

433
00:29:27,934 --> 00:29:30,164
Look at some of this stuff.

434
00:29:40,947 --> 00:29:43,609
Bee kisses.

435
00:29:53,760 --> 00:29:55,694
Hi.

436
00:29:55,762 --> 00:29:57,696
- Hi.
- You mind if I sit down?

437
00:30:23,690 --> 00:30:27,626
Hah? Well, then,
hello, hello.

438
00:30:27,694 --> 00:30:29,218
Oh, look at--

439
00:30:42,075 --> 00:30:45,067
Yee-haah!
Yee-haah!

440
00:30:45,144 --> 00:30:49,171
Whoa! Whoa!
Yee-haah!

441
00:30:49,248 --> 00:30:51,842
Come on, buddy!
Whee-haah!

442
00:30:53,086 --> 00:30:55,680
What is going on here?

443
00:31:09,302 --> 00:31:11,862
Sit down.

444
00:31:11,938 --> 00:31:15,465
Get in your beds right now.

445
00:31:15,541 --> 00:31:17,509
Sit down! Sit down!

446
00:31:19,712 --> 00:31:23,011
Lie down in your beds
right now!

447
00:31:23,082 --> 00:31:26,347
- I've checked up on you, Hunter.
- Patch.

448
00:31:26,419 --> 00:31:29,354
Hunter, Dr. Prack was
a colleague of mine at Bringham.

449
00:31:29,422 --> 00:31:31,856
He tells me
you have a brilliant mind...

450
00:31:31,924 --> 00:31:36,452
and, like many brilliant people,
you don't necessarily think
the rules apply to you.

451
00:31:36,529 --> 00:31:39,965
Not all the rules, sir, but the Golden
Rule, I think that applies to everyone.

452
00:31:40,032 --> 00:31:41,966
Don't you, sir?

453
00:31:42,034 --> 00:31:46,198
I've also heard you have
a real passion to be a doctor, Hunter.

454
00:31:46,272 --> 00:31:48,206
Patch.

455
00:31:48,274 --> 00:31:52,176
Truth of it is, Hunter,
passion doesn't make doctors.

456
00:31:52,245 --> 00:31:54,645
I make doctors.

457
00:31:54,714 --> 00:31:56,648
Understood?

458
00:31:56,716 --> 00:31:59,207
- Understood.
- Good.

459
00:31:59,285 --> 00:32:04,077
Medical students, as a rule,
have no contact with patients
until the third year.

460
00:32:04,478 --> 00:32:06,002
- Is that clear?
- It is, sir, but don't you think--

461
00:32:06,079 --> 00:32:10,516
Our way of doing things
is a product of centuries of experience.

462
00:32:12,019 --> 00:32:13,953
It's all there for a reason.

463
00:32:17,524 --> 00:32:19,958
It's my hospital.

464
00:32:20,027 --> 00:32:22,962
I know everything
that goes on inside of it.

465
00:32:24,698 --> 00:32:26,632
Everything.

466
00:32:28,568 --> 00:32:30,502
Deviation of the tongue.

467
00:32:30,570 --> 00:32:32,538
- A problem with the cranial nerve.
- Which side?

468
00:32:32,606 --> 00:32:35,040
- Right side, tenth nerve.
- Twelfth nerve.

469
00:32:35,108 --> 00:32:38,043
Do you know how many billions of dollars
are wasted on malpractice insurance?

470
00:32:38,111 --> 00:32:41,046
That's money that goes to lawyers
that could go to patients.

471
00:32:41,114 --> 00:32:45,210
- Hi, guys. Sorry I'm late.
- Everybody know Carin Fisher,
Adelane's roommate?

472
00:32:45,285 --> 00:32:48,220
I invited her to join
our study group.

473
00:32:50,390 --> 00:32:53,325
So, Carin, why do you
want to be a doctor?

474
00:32:53,393 --> 00:32:56,328
Is it just me, or do we
have a lot of work to do?

475
00:32:56,396 --> 00:32:58,921
It's just a question.
I think it's the question.

476
00:32:58,999 --> 00:33:01,661
Actually, I don't find the question
here in the outline.

477
00:33:01,735 --> 00:33:04,067
- What page are you on?
- Uh, 1432.

478
00:33:04,137 --> 00:33:05,900
Deviation of a tongue.

479
00:33:05,973 --> 00:33:08,533
We'd learn more if we were
working closely with patients.

480
00:33:08,608 --> 00:33:11,702
That's why we're studying--
to learn enough to help the patients.

481
00:33:11,778 --> 00:33:14,212
Adelane, don't waste your breath.

482
00:33:14,281 --> 00:33:16,215
Don't you th--

483
00:33:16,283 --> 00:33:18,615
Don't you think
I see through you?

484
00:33:18,685 --> 00:33:21,620
You act like you're above the system
when you're really just a nonconformist.

485
00:33:21,688 --> 00:33:23,622
You have to get
under the fingernails...

486
00:33:23,690 --> 00:33:26,124
of any authority figure
that crosses your path...

487
00:33:26,193 --> 00:33:28,423
as a way of dealing
with some insecurity.

488
00:33:28,495 --> 00:33:30,429
Antisocial personality, I believe.
Intriguing diagnosis.

489
00:33:30,497 --> 00:33:34,126
Truman, this isn't funny. Smart people
flunk out of here all the time.

490
00:33:34,201 --> 00:33:38,604
Yeah, uh, odds are one of
